Example: Urbana Open Expenditure

Data Source: State of Illinois Data Portal https://data.illinois.gov/

Urbana Open Expenditure Dataset Link

This dataset contains payment details that are the source for the Urbana Cityâs Open Expenditures website. The data was last updated on March 9th, 2025, covering records from fiscal years 2013 to 2025. The dataset includes 166K rows and 25 columns.

library(tidyverse)

Here,

  • sortVar = TRUE â sort variables from high to low fractions of missing values.
  • The Percentage of missing values per variable plot contains a barplot showing fractions of missing values per variable.
  • In the Occurrence of missing data patterns plot, a value that is missing is colored red, and the observed values are colored light blue.

Remove Columns with High Missing Values

OE <- OE %>%
  select(-c(payment_method, invoice_line_distribution_number,
            purchase_order_line_number, purchase_order_number))

In this dataset, the numerical variable amount variable has no missing values. Please refer to âAdditional Notes for Urbana Open Expenditure Dataâ for more information on linear regression-based imputation for imputing numerical variables.

Better Data Visualization

library(kableExtra) 
# Ensure the `kableExtra` package is installed to knit this Rmd file smoothly.

Five guidelines for better data visualizations from Jon Schwabishâs book called Better Data Visualizations.

  • Show the data
  • Avoid the spaghetti chart
  • Reduce the clutter
  • Integrate the graphics and text
  • Start with gray

Data Visualization Guideline 1: Show the Data

âYour reader can only grasp your point, argument, or story if they see the data. â Jon Schwabishâ

Choose the right charts and graphs for the job:

  • Visualizing Relationships: The Impact of Scatterplots

  • Tracking Trends: The Impact of Line Graphs

  • Comparing Multicategories: The Role of Bar Charts

  • Exploring Data Clusters: Insights from Histograms and Box Plots

    • Histograms and box plots show where your data is clustered and can compare categories.

  • Pie Charts: Enhancing Visualization Details

    • Pie charts are powerful for adding detail to other visualizations, but arenât as effective on their own.
    • Bar charts are favored over pie charts.

  • More R chart examples can be find at The R Graph Gallery

Five Important Graphs Summary (Base R vs ggplot)

Base R graphics

# scatterplot
  plot(x, y)

# linegraph
  plot(x, y, type="l")
  ## Add another line to the plot
  lines(x, z)

  #linegraph with dots
  plot(x, y, type="b")



# histogram
  hist(x)


# boxplot
  boxplot(y)
  boxplot(y ~ x)






# barplot of variable x
  counts=table(x)
  barplot(counts)

Graphics using ggplot

# scatterplot
ggplot(data=df, mapping=aes(x=xvar, y=yvar)) +
  geom_point()

# linegraph
ggplot(data=df, mapping=aes(x=xvar, y=yvar)) +
  geom_line()

  #linegraph with dots
  ggplot(data=df, mapping=aes(x=xvar, y=yvar)) +
    geom_line() +
    geom_point()

# histogram
ggplot(data=df, mapping=aes(x=xvar)) +
  geom_histogram()

# boxplot
  # boxplot of one variable yvar
  ggplot(data=df, mapping=aes(y=yvar)) +
    geom_boxplot()
  # boxplot of the yvar vs xvar
  ggplot(data=df, mapping=aes(x=xvar, y=yvar)) +
    geom_boxplot()


# barplot of variable x
  # If not pre-counted, use geom_bar()
  ggplot(data=df, mapping=aes(x=xvar))+
   geom_bar()
  # If precounted, use geom_col()
  ggplot(data=df_counted, mapping=aes(x=xvar,y=counts))+
    geom_col()

Data Visualization Guideline 1 Continue

Urbana Open Expenditure â Total Expenditure by Date and Department

Step 1: Convert the payment_date column to a date-time object, then extract and retain only the date (dropping the time component).

Step 2: Sum the amount by payment_date and department to calculate daysum.

library(lubridate)

OE <- OE %>% mutate(payment_date = as.Date(mdy_hms(payment_date)))

OE_daysum <- OE %>%
  group_by(payment_date, department) %>%
  summarize(daysum = sum(amount)) # Daily total expenditure

Step 3: Draw the line chart. Use labs() to add the x-label, y-label, and title.

OE_daysum %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = payment_date, y = daysum, color = department)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x="Payment Date",
       y="Daily Total Expenditure",
       title = "Total Expenditure by Date and Department")+
  theme_minimal()

Data Visualization Guideline 1 Continue â remove outliers using IQR rule

The plot above shows some negative expenditures, likely resulting from refunds, reimbursements, corrections, or similar adjustments. Moreover, we observe some unusually large values.

From now on, we only consider the positive expenditures.

OE <- OE %>% 
  filter(amount > 0)

OE %>% ggplot(aes(x=amount)) + geom_histogram() # Extremely right-skewed

OE %>% ggplot(aes(x = log(amount))) + geom_histogram() # roughly symmetric

Transform the data using the natural logarithm to reduce skewness. Then use an IQR-based outlier detection method.We may adjusting the multiplier, i.e.Â use a larger multiplier (e.g., 2.5 or 3) instead of the common multiplier 1.5 for more conservative filtering.

OE <- OE %>% 
  mutate(logamount = log(amount),
         Q1 = quantile(logamount, 0.25),
         Q3 = quantile(logamount, 0.75),
         IQR = Q3 - Q1,
         lower_threshold = Q1 - 2.5 * IQR, 
         upper_threshold = Q3 + 2.5 * IQR) %>%
  # We apply large multiplier 2.5 here, instead of 1.5
  filter(logamount < upper_threshold & logamount > lower_threshold) %>% 
  # Remove outliers using the IQR rule
  select(-c(logamount, Q1, Q3, IQR, lower_threshold, upper_threshold))
  # remove the newly created variables from the data frame
  • We regenerate the previous visualization after excluding outliers.
OE_daysum <- OE %>%
  group_by(payment_date, department) %>%
  summarize(daysum = sum(amount), .groups = "drop") # Daily total expenditure

OE_daysum %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = payment_date, y = daysum, color = department)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x="Payment Date",
       y="Daily Total Expenditure",
       title = "Total Expenditure by Date and Department")+
  theme_minimal()

Data Visualization Guideline 2: Avoid the Spaghetti Chart

âSometimes we face the challenge of including lots of data in a single graph but we donât need to try to pack everything into a single graph.

Faceting or using small multiples is a useful way to de-clutter a busy data visualization. Faceting is a very natural method in ggplot2. With effective small multiples, if a reader understand how to read one small multiple then they should understand how to read all of the multiples. Two tips:

  1. Arrange the small multiples in a logical order
  2. Use the same layout, size, font, and color in each small multiple

We modify the line chart from the previous section

p1 <- # the previous plot
  OE_daysum %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = payment_date, y = daysum, color = department)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x="Payment Date",
       y="Daily Total Expenditure")+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(title = "Without facet_wrap()")

OE_daysum %>% 
  group_by(department) %>% 
  summarise(sum=sum(daysum)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(sum)) %>% 
  head(7)
## # A tibble: 7 Ã 2
##   department                   sum
##   <chr>                      <dbl>
## 1 PUBLIC WORKS          176350245.
## 2 NOT APPLICABLE        101240028.
## 3 COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT  84771247.
## 4 POLICE                 74952680.
## 5 FIRE AND RESCUE        42718122.
## 6 FINANCE                41125517.
## 7 GENERAL SERVICES       24745632.
p2 <- OE_daysum %>%
  filter(department %in% c("PUBLIC WORKS", "COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT", "POLICE", 
                           "FIRE AND RESCUE", "FINANCE", "GENERAL SERVICES"
                           )) %>% 
  mutate(department = factor(department, 
         levels = c("PUBLIC WORKS", "COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT", "POLICE", 
                  "FIRE AND RESCUE", "FINANCE", "GENERAL SERVICES") #save order
                      )) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = payment_date, y = daysum)) +
  geom_line() + 
  labs(x="Payment Date",
       y="Daily Total Expenditure")+
  theme_minimal()+
  facet_wrap(~department)+
  labs(title = "With facet_wrap()")

library(grid)
library(gridExtra)
grid.arrange(p1, p2, nrow=2,
             top=textGrob("Avoid the Spaghetti Chart by faceting or using small multiples"))

Data Visualization Guideline 3: Reduce the Clutter

âThe use of unnecessary visual elements distracts your reader from the central idea and clutters the page.â

A few things to avoid:

  • heavy tick marks and grid lines
  • unnecessary 3d
  • excessive text

Consider this image from Claus Wilkeâs Fundamentalâs of Data Visualization.

How many passengers are in first class? How many male passengers are in 3rd class? Letâs recreate this plot without the gratuitous 3D.

Titanic Example

The titanic data set

titanic <- tribble(
  ~Class, ~Sex, ~n,
  "1st class", "female passengers", 144,
  "1st class", "male passengers", 179,
  "2nd class", "female passengers", 106,
  "2nd class", "male passengers", 171,
  "3rd class", "female passengers", 216,
  "3rd class", "male passengers", 493
)

Recreate the 3D plot in 2D.

ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Class, y = n, fill = Sex)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 800, 100)) +
  geom_text(aes(label = n), position = position_stack(0.5))

Data Visualization Guideline 4: Integrate the Graphics and Text

  1. Remove legends when possible and label data directly
  2. Write an active title like a newspaper headline
  3. Add explainers

labs() adds title, subtitle, caption, and tag to ggplot2 objects. It can also be used to overwrite x, y, and legend titles. Use NULL to remove a label entirely (not "").

Titanic Example (ctn)

library(ggtext)

ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Class, y = n, fill = Sex)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 800, 100)) +
  geom_text(aes(label = n), vjust = 1.5, 
            position = position_dodge(.9),
            color = "white") +
  labs(title = "All three classes had more <span style = 'color:#00BFC4;'>male passengers</span> than <span style = 'color:#F8766D;'>female passengers</span>",
    subtitle = "(Number of passengers)",
    caption = "Data from library(titanic)",
    x = NULL,
    y = NULL
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +  
  theme(plot.title = element_markdown(hjust = 0.5)) +
  guides(fill = "none")

Data Visualization Guideline 5: Start with Gray

âWhenever you make a graph, start with all gray data elements. By doing so, you force yourself to be purposeful and strategic in your use of color, labels, and other elements.â

library(gghighlight) complements this idea of starting with gray.

Cumulative Expenditure Example

Data Visualization Guideline 5 Continue â steps for generating the previous plot

Step 1: Compute the cumulative sum of amount over the years.

OE.cumsum <- OE %>%
  mutate(budget_category = ifelse(budget_category == "INTERFUND & TFR OUT", 
                                  "INTERFUND & TFRS OUT", budget_category), 
         budget_category = ifelse(budget_category == "CONTRACTUAL SERVCS", 
                                  "CONTRACTUAL SERVICES", budget_category)) %>%  
  arrange(payment_date, budget_category) %>% 
  group_by(budget_category) %>%
  mutate(cumsum = cumsum(amount))

Step 2: Create a line plot with x = payment_date, y = cumsum, group = budget_category, and geom_line()

OE.cumsum %>%
  ggplot(aes(payment_date, cumsum, group = budget_category))+
  geom_line()

Note: If we simply create a line graph with color = budget_category, then

OE.cumsum %>%
  ggplot(aes(payment_date, cumsum, color = budget_category))+
  geom_line()

Step 3: Add the following code to clean up the x-axis and y-axis.

labs(x = "Payment Date",
     y = "Cumulative Amount",
     title = "Budget Category Expenditures: Cumulative Totals (FY2013-FY2025)")

Step 4: Suppose we want to highlight the three budget categories with the highest amounts. We can use library(gghighlight). Switch group to color in your existing code and add gghighlight(max(cumsum) > 75000000).

Step 5: Above the data viz, add theme_minimal(). Or run theme_set(theme_minimal()), which changes the default theme for the entire R session.

Put everything together.

library(gghighlight)

OE %>% 
  mutate(budget_category = ifelse(budget_category == "INTERFUND & TFR OUT", 
                                  "INTERFUND & TFRS OUT", budget_category), 
         budget_category = ifelse(budget_category == "CONTRACTUAL SERVCS", 
                                  "CONTRACTUAL SERVICES", budget_category)) %>%  
  arrange(payment_date, budget_category) %>%
  group_by(budget_category) %>%
  mutate(cumsum = cumsum(amount)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(payment_date, cumsum, color=budget_category, 
             group=budget_category))+
  geom_line()+
  labs(x = "Payment Date",
     y = "Cumulative Amount",
     title = "Budget Category Expenditures: Cumulative Totals (FY2013-FY2025)")+
  gghighlight(max(cumsum) > 75000000)+
  theme_minimal()

Time Series Plots

Standard ACF/PACF plots require evenly spaced time intervals. For irregularly spaced data like payment_date, we can create regular time bins (e.g., using fiscal_year and fiscal_year_period) before analysis.

  • Create combined = fiscal_year-fiscal_year_period pattern
OE <- OE %>%
  mutate(combined = paste(fiscal_year,
                          sprintf("%02d", fiscal_year_period), sep = "-")) %>% 
  arrange(combined)

Time Series Plot

OE %>%   
  filter(budget_category %in% c("CAPITAL OUTLAY")) %>%
  group_by(combined, budget_category) %>% 
  summarise(periodtotal = sum(amount)) %>% 
  arrange(combined, budget_category) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = combined, y = periodtotal, group = budget_category))+
  geom_line()+
  labs(x = "Fiscal Year Period",
       y = "Period Total Expenditure",
       title = "Capital Outlay Budget Expenditures Across Fiscal Year Periods")+
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

ACF

OE %>%   
  filter(budget_category %in% c("CAPITAL OUTLAY")) %>%
  group_by(combined, budget_category) %>% 
  summarise(periodtotal = sum(amount)) %>% 
  arrange(combined, budget_category) %>% 
  pull(periodtotal) %>% 
  acf(lag.max = 50)

PACF

OE %>%   
  filter(budget_category %in% c("CAPITAL OUTLAY")) %>%
  group_by(combined, budget_category) %>% 
  summarise(periodtotal = sum(amount)) %>% 
  arrange(combined, budget_category) %>% 
  pull(periodtotal) %>% 
  pacf()

The ACF or PACF plot at lag 12 is outside of the confidence interval (blue dashed lines), it indicates a significant correlation at lag 12 (i.e.Â strong yearly seasonal effect with 12 months = 1 year).

Main Takeaways

  • Check the missing values
  • Choose the right charts and graphs for the job. Show the information clearly is the key!
  • Avoid the spaghetti chart by faceting or using small multiples.
  • Reduce the clutter and avoid 3D plots!
  • Integrate the graphics and text in a smart and seamless manner.
  • Start with gray, start from simple.
